-Limited facility access;

-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;

-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and

-24/7 remote monitoring with emergency shutdown capabilities.



General Release Mitigation include:



-Automatic and remotely operated shut-offs to limit release quantities;

-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks;

-Hydrocarbon detectors at key areas to warn of a chemical release and initiate a terminal shutdown;

-Deluge system installed in offload area; and

-Vessel fire water monitors installed along with a fire/pressure rated intumescent vessel coating.



General Emergency Response include:



-An emergency alert system;

-Periodic emergency training for employees;

-Communication systems with local emergency responders and regulatory agencies;

-Emergency drills with plant personnel, regulatory agencies, and community emergency responders to enhance response skills and coordination among agencies;

-Mutual Aid with Local Fire Departments (Primary response is Charlotte Fire Department Station 21); and

-Charlotte Fire Department and Mecklenburg County Emergency Management.



Further, the Charlotte East Terminal butane process complies with the National Fire Protection Association's (NFPA's) Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) Code (NFPA-58) requirements for LP Gas storage. In addition to the presence of appropriate controls to prevent possible releases of butane, if a release does occur, a Facility Response Plan (FRP)/Emergency Response Action Plan (ERAP) is in place with the response activities being coordinated with the Charlotte Fire Department, and Mecklenburg County Emergency Management.



